message.text:
Bangkok (Thailand): [Japanese Films Screenings] 
Dec. 19 "The Chef of South Polar (南極料理人)"
Dec. 26 "Nodojiman – Sing Your Heart Out (のど自慢）"
http://www.jfbkk.or.th/Theater_201412_eg.php#004

Eat delicious Japanese food in extreme place...
My friend has told me that eating a cup ramen at the top of Mt.Fuji (in extreme cold weather) is by far his best meal he has ever had so far. 
What would you eat if you were at the South Pole? I would choose....SUKIYAKI!

極限の場所でおいしい日本食を食べる・・・
私の友だちは（とっても寒い）富士山の上で食べたカップラーメンが今までで一番おいしかったごはんだと話していました。あなたがもし南極にいたら何を食べたいですか？私は・・・すき焼き！

message.text:
#Hiragana Master
Say it Together! Basic Japanese Words in Japanese Alphabetical Order.
Today's Word is "HO" HOSHI　#nihongo
日本の単語を五十音順にわかりやすく紹介！「ほ」し（星、Star）
http://words.marugotoweb.jp/search_detail.php?id=1983&p=1&q=%E6%98%9F&source=search&lang=en

Hello everyone! The shivering winter is really here in Japan...
On the other hand, this is the very season when lots of beautiful stars can be seen clearly!
For example, as you know, we can enjoy the three stars in Orion's Belt, the Winter Triangle...and so on 

In Japan, since the bright stars make us think of something hopeful and positive, we often call a person to whom we'd like to count on, "Star of Hope"（希望の星/Kibou no Hoshi or 期待の星/Kitai no Hoshi）.

Why don't you look up the sky and search for your favorite star tonight;)? (Unless it is not cloudy or rainy like in Tokyo today...)

日本にも、さむーい冬到来です。でも、この寒い季節が、「星」が一番きれいに見えますよね。

日本では、頼れる人のことを「希望の星」「期待の星」と言ったりしますが、光輝く星のもつ希望に満ちた前向きなイメージが連想されますよね！

今日も、ぜひ星空を見上げてみてはいかがでしょ～？（東京はあいにくの雨ですが・・・TxT)

message.text:
Malaysia: Dec.13-Jan.11 Revive the Legend – Revitalising Japan’s Traditional Colours from the Nature of Asia
マレーシア：12-13/1/11染織史家・吉岡幸雄氏による日本古来の美しい植物染展
Come and be mesmerised by the long-lost art of Japanese dyeing at master dyer Sachio Yoshioka’s first solo show in Malaysia. The exhibition will feature 36 fabrics and related paraphernalia in a spellbinding journey through the country’s cultural heritage.The basis for his inspiration is Genji Monogatari (The Tale of Genji), written in the early 11th century by noblewoman Murasaki Shikibu and widely considered to be the world’s first novel.

Did you know? The traditional colors of Japan mostly originate from the names of plants, flowers, and animals that bore or resemble them. Can you name a few? 
http://www.tombow.com/sp/irojiten/

染色界の第一人者で、日本の伝統色の再現に半生をかけて挑んできた染織史家・吉岡幸雄氏の作品を展示。ドキュメンタリー映画の上映とトークも。
